<br>
Some would make a statement in absolute, others will try and clarify.<br>
<br>
Some support their arguments, others don't.<br>
<br>
Some intend to antagonise or derail an argument, others wish to correct a percieved flaw.<br>
<br>
The problem here is it's hard to tell at times.<br>
<br>
To take up your example;<br>
<br>
If I jumped off that tower, I may be able to miss the pavement and fly. It is a view. But until I have done it, the view is unproven. I may go splat, as have so many people before - which is the proof that supports your view. Indeed, that is most likely unless there is some key difference in what I do to what others have done.<br>
<br>
It may also be that I am paraphrasing something else, but in a 'reasoned' argument, I would also be expected to give credit to the source, or at least indicate what I base such an argument on.<br>
<br>
However, having seem many arguments in various forums, news groups et al, I have come to see that people don't think about structuring their arguments, qualifying or quantifying them. But that is because they don't engage in 'formal' arguments. They simply have their say and care little about any counter argument.<br>
<br>
It's a case of pick who you engage in an argument with, and who you respond to - or if a responce is needed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lilstryven>Lil Stryven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Big Gnome<br>
